Projective Textures
Motivation
  • Spotlights
  • Movie/Slide projectors
  • Headlights
  • Stained glass
  • Superhero logos
Example
  • Here’s the scene we want to render
Example
  • Here’s the projected image
Idea
  • Define a camera located at the light source, looking in direction of the translucent object
    • This camera has viewMatrix and projMatrix
    • Suppose we send in a uniform mat4 projTexMatrix
      • projTexMatrix = viewMatrix * projMatrix
  • Then we draw the scene
Shader
  • VS will do vertex processing as usual
  • No changes here
Shader
  • In FS, we have an additional texture input
    • Holds projected image (ex: Stained glass image)
    • Suppose it’s called projectedTexture
  • FS does lighting computations as usual
  • But at the end, we do some additional steps
Shader
  • FS puts world space point into virtual camera’s “screen space”
    • vec4 p = …world space point…
    • p = p * projTexMatrix;
    • p /= p.w; //p.xy in range -1…1
    • p.xy += vec2(1.0); //p.xy in range 0…2
    • p.xy *= 0.5; //p.xy in range 0…1
  • Sample from projectedTexture:
    • vec4 pc = texture( projectedTexture, vec3(p.xy,0.0));
  • Mix pc with previously computed color
    • Ex: color.rgb += pc.rgb;
  • Let’s fire it up and see what we get!
Results
  • Wow! That’s wild!
Solution
  • Must set texture mode to clamp instead of repeat
  • Suppose we declare texture like so in FS:
    layout(binding=10) uniform sampler2DArray projectedTexture
  • Then on CPU we’d create a Sampler with clamping mode:
    Sampler clampsamp{Sampler::Type::MIPMAP, Sampler::Wrap::CLAMP};
  • And bind it to texture unit 10:
    clampsamp.bind(10);
  • Projective image should have 1 pixel wide black border
  • And set sampler to use linear minification instead of mipmap
    • For better quality: Manually generate all mip levels, force black border on each
Result
Modification
  • We need to omit projection on any face that’s a backface with respect to light source
  • Add a uniform:
    vec3 projectorLocation;
  • CPU side: Set it to match projector camera’s eye
  • FS:
vec3 toProjector = projectorLocation - v_worldPos;
if( dot( toProjector, N ) < 0 ){
    //don't add pc to color
}
Result
Problem
  • This produces a sharp cutoff where surfaces transition from facing light to not facing light
  • Ex: Closeup of column:
Better
  • Scale brightness of projected image according to how closely surface is facing light source
  • This basically applies Lambert’s cosine law
vec3 toProjector = normalize(projectorLocation - v_worldPos);
float projDot = dot(toProjector,N);
projDot = max( projDot, 0.0 );
vec4 p = vec4(v_worldPos,1.0);
p = p * projTexMatrix
p /= p.w;
p.xy += vec2(1.0);
p.xy *= 0.5;
vec4 pc = texture( projectedTexture, vec3(p.xy,0.0));
color.rgb += projDot * pc.rgb;
Result
  • Especially looks better on columns (no abrupt cutoff)
Question
  • We’ve been glossing over one key point: What should the projector camera’s field of view be?
  • Assume we know:
    • Position of projector light source. Call it s.
    • Center of translucent object
      • This will be the coi of the projector camera. Call it c.
    • width and height of translucent object
  • We can then compute point v: v = c + height * vec3(0,0.5,0)
    • Assume translucent object is axis aligned
Strategy
  • We have a triangle
  • And we know all three vertices of that triangle: c, v, s
  • We want angle θ
  • We can use the law of cosines
Law of Cosines
  • Let C, V, and S be lengths of three sides of triangle as shown
  • Law of cosines: S2 = V2 + C2 − 2VCcos θ
  • Rearrange: cos θ = (S2 − V2 − C2)/( − 2VC)
  • Take arccos to get θ
  • This is vertical field of view
  • Do same procedure to get horizontal field of view
Problem
  • Objects behind the projector are also illuminated
  • Projection equations don’t distinguish with regard to depth
  • Need to verify that z value of projected point is positive
    • Compute p = p * projTexMatrix
    • Then: If p.z < 0: Don’t add projColor into FS output color
    • Otherwise, do rest of steps as outlined previously
Haze
  • What if we want to simulate a hazy environment?
  • In haze, light experiences inscattering and outscattering due to tiny particles in air
  • Inscatter can be single, double, triple or more
Haze
  • We’ve already seen how to simulate outscattering: Fog
  • The longer a ray passes through the scattering medium, the more chance it has to undergo outscattering
float distWorld = distance(eyePos,v_worldPos);
float fogAmount = smoothstep( 0, 20, distWorld );
color.rgb = mix( color.rgb, fogColor, fogAmount );
Inscattering
  • It’s challenging to simulate double or triple inscattering
  • So we’ll restrict our attempt to single inscattering
  • Fortunately: Single is responsible for most visual appearance
Consider
  • Inscattering is not just a function of the distance a ray passes through the scattering medium
  • It also depends on how much of that medium is lit
    • More inscattering appears along the path to the blue ball
    • Some inscattering along path to purple one
    • No inscattering along path to green ball
  • But how can we measure this?
Ray Marching
  • We’ll use the strategy of ray marching
    • Begin at the eye
    • Sample at various points on the ray
    • Accumulate results
Strategy
  • Let p = v_worldPos
  • Let V = normalize( eyePos - v_worldPos );
    • We might already have this (ex: for Phong lighting)
  • Let delta = 0.05 * normalize(V)
    • Smaller increments = better quality, but more time
  • Loop:
float remaining = distance(eyePos,v_worldPos);
while( remaining > 0 ){
    tmp = p *  projTexMatrix
    tmp /= tmp.w; tmp.xy += vec2(1.0); tmp.xy *= 0.5;
    pc = texture( projectedTexture, vec3(p.xy,0.0));
    total += pc
    p += delta
    remaining -= 0.05;  //same increment as for delta
}
Problem
  • This involves a matrix-vector multiply for each ray-marched point
  • Not that bad, but a bit costly
  • We can get better performance by ray-marching in texture space
Idea
  • Transform eyePos into projector’s texture space
  • Transform object’s world space point into projector’s texture space
  • Step along that segment and accumulate texture colors
  • Number of steps should be proportional to world space distance from eye to object
Code
//assume we have vec3 p == v_worldPos in
//projector's texture space

//p1 = eye transformed to projector's texture space
//Note: Could send p1 in as a uniform
vec4 p1 = vec4(eyePos.xyz,1) * projTexMatrix;
p1 /= p1.w;
p1.xy += vec2(1.0);
p1.xy *= 0.5;

//distance from eye to point we're shading
float distWorld = distance(eyePos,v_worldPos);

//lower value = better quality but slower
float sampStep = 0.05/distWorld;

vec3 total=vec3(0);         //accumulated total

for(float q=0.0;q<=1.0;q+=sampStep){
    vec2 tc = mix(p1.xy,p.xy,q);
    total += texture( projectedTexture, vec3(tc,0.0) ).rgb;
}

//multiplier matches step size
color.rgb += 0.05*total;
Result
  • Scene with and without fog
Note
  • Some issues:
    • Step size is a bit too large: You can see the “noise” in the light rays
    • No shadows: Column should shadow the light
      • And prevent inscattering
    • Framerate is low (this was using integrated GPU: Texture fetches are especially slow)
Appendix
  • What if translucent object isn’t axis aligned?
  • Or we want to tile a texture across its surface?
  • One possible solution: Raytracing
    • Only use for this one part: Not too computationally intensive
    • Do in shader → Leverage GPU power
Raytracing
  • Basic idea: Let Q = mesh for translucent object (ex: window)
  • For the point we are shading:
    • Compute ip = intersection of (ray from p to light) and (plane of Q)
    • For all triangles t in Q
      • if ip is inside t:
        • Use texture from t
Setup
  • All work will be done in fragment shader
  • Input data we will need:
    • Coordinates of triangles making up Q
    • Texture coordinates of triangles
  • We can pack this data into a texture
    • Row i holds data about triangle i
    • Texels (0,i), (1,i), (2,i) = vertices of one triangle
    • Texels (3,i), (4,i), (5,i) = texture coordinates
  • We could pack data to reduce space requirements
    • For simplicity, we don’t do that here
Example
  • Suppose we have this data from our mesh:
    • vector<vec3> positions
    • vector<vec2> texcoords
    • vector<uint32_t> indices
  • All of these are available when the Mesh is loaded
Example
  • On CPU: Here’s how we would create the texture
  • Each texel is a vec4
vector<float> data;
for(size_t i=0;i<indices.size();i+=3){
    for(int j=0;j<3;++j){
        uint32_t idx = indices[i+j];
        vec3 p = positions[idx];
        data.push_back( p.x );
        data.push_back( p.y );
        data.push_back( p.z );
        data.push_back( 1.0 );
    }
    for(int j=0;j<3;++j){
        uint32_t idx = indices[i+j];
        vec2 t = texcoords[idx];
        data.push_back( t.x );
        data.push_back( t.y );
        data.push_back( 0 );
        data.push_back( 0 );
    }
}

std::shared_ptr<DataTexture2DArray> windowMeshData =
    std::make_shared<DataTexture2DArray>(
        7, indices.size()/3, 1, GL_RGBA32F,
        GL_RGBA, GL_FLOAT, data.data() );
Draw
  • CPU side:
    • Activate shader
    • Set all uniforms
      • window texture
    • Bind windowMeshData to a free texture unit
  • We still have projectedTexture bound to a different texture unit
    • Remember, this is the image itself
Fragment Shader
//texture width is always 6
//texture height = number of triangles
int num_tris = textureSize( windowMeshTexture )[1];
raydir = lightPos - v_worldPos;
vec2 q = vec2(0,0);
for(i=0;i<num_tris;++i){
    P = computeRayIntersection( i, lightPos, raydir );
    if( P is inside triangle ){
        q=...texcoord at P...
        break;
    }
}
//sample projectiveTexture texture at q
//add to output color
Ray Intersection
vec3 computeRayIntersection( int tidx, vec3 rayStart, vec3 rayDir ){
    //...
}
  • Input: Triangle index, ray start and direction
  • Need to compute intersection point of ray with plane containing triangle
Steps
  • First, get vertices of triangle:
    • vec3 v0 = texelFetch( windowMeshTexture, ivec3(tidx,0)).xyz;
    • vec3 v1 = texelFetch( windowMeshTexture, ivec3(tidx,1)).xyz;
    • vec3 v2 = texelFetch( windowMeshTexture, ivec3(tidx,2)).xyz;
  • Get normal for triangle:
    • vec3 N = normalize( cross( v2-v1, v0-v1) );
Ray Intersection
  • If translucent object can move: We’ll need to send its worldMatrix to the shader
    • Transform v0, v1, v2, N by that worldMatrix
      • Not the worldMatrix for the object we’re drawing!
    • If projective object can’t move, we don’t need to worry about this
  • Compute plane equation: Ax+By+Cz+D=0
    • A,B,C = N
    • Compute: D = -N · v0
Plane
  • Now we need to find a point p such that Nxpx + Nypy + Nzpz + D = 0
  • Restriction: p must be on the ray
  • So p must also satisfy the equation rayStart + t * rayDir
    • For some t > 0
  • Let s be the ray start and d be the ray direction
  • Then we want: Nx(sx + tdx) + Ny(sy + tdy) + Nz(sz + tdz) + D = 0
    • Only one unknown: t
Ray Intersection
  • We can show that t =  − (N⋅s + D)/(N⋅d)
    • If t negative: no intersection
  • Compute intersection point:
    • p = s + t*d
  • We now need to determine if p is inside triangle tidx
  • We’ll use idea of barycentric coordinates
Barycentric
  • Any point inside a triangle can be written as an affine combination of triangle vertices.
    • Like a weighted average of each vertex
    • Call them a,b,c
    • Ex: If we are at A: a=1, b=0, c=0
    • If we are at the indicated point: Maybe
      a=0.2, b=0.1, c=0.7
    • If a,b,c all positive: P is inside triangle; else not
Barycentric
  • Given triangle vertices v0, v1, v2 & point p: Find barycentric weights a,b,c
    • First, make points relative to v0:
      • p’ = p-v0
      • v1’ = v1-p
      • v2’ = v2-A
    • Now we know that:
      p’ = b v1’ + c v2’
Barycentric
  • We have three equations, two unknowns:
    • p’x = bv1x’ + cv2x’
    • Same for y, z
  • Solve for b
    • b = (px’ − cv2x’)/(v1x’)
    • Then substitute into one of remaining equations, solve for c
  • Problem: What if v1x’ = 0?
    • Could use series of if-tests to choose two of equations to use
    • That’s cumbersome
Better Way
  • Lengyel (see references) shows we can rewrite it:
    • Start with: p’ = b v1’ + c v2’
  • Take dot product on both sides with v1’ and then v2’:
    • p’ · v1’ = (b v1’ + c v2’) · v1’
    • p’ · v2’ = (b v1’ + c v2’) · v2’
  • From properties of dot product: Distribute:
    • p’ · v1’ = b v1’ · v1’ + c v2’ · v1’
    • p’ · v2’ = b v1’ · v1’ + c v2’ · v2’
Better Way
  • Then rewrite the two equations as a matrix operation
    • You can multiply it out to verify it’s all correct
⎡⎢⎣ p’ v1’     p’ v2’ ⎤⎥⎦ = ⎡⎢⎣ v1’⋅v1’ v2’⋅v1’     v1’⋅v2’ v2’⋅v2’ ⎤⎥⎦⎡⎢⎣ b   c ⎤⎥⎦
Better Way
  • Compute the inverse of the 2x2 matrix to get:
⎡⎢⎣ ⋅   ⋅ ⎤⎥⎦ = ⎡⎢⎣ b   c ⎤⎥⎦
  • So we just need the inverse of the 2x2 matrix and we know b and c
  • Since a+b+c=1, we know a=1-b-c
Inverse
  • Let BB = v1’ · v1’ , CC = v2’ · v2’ , BC= v1’ · v2’
  • Let:
M = ⎡⎢⎣ CC  − BC      − BC BB ⎤⎥⎦
  • Claim: Matrix inverse is (1)/(BB*CC − BC*BC)⋅M
Barycentric
  • Once we know b and c: Compute: a=1-b-c
  • If all three are positive: p lies inside triangle
  • What about texture coordinates at p?
  • Easy, once we have barycentric coordinates
    • Let t0, t1, t2 be texture coordinates at the three vertices
    • vec3 t0 = texelFetch( windowMeshTexture, ivec3(tidx,3)).xyz;
    • vec3 t1 = texelFetch( windowMeshTexture, ivec3(tidx,4)).xyz;
    • vec3 t2 = texelFetch( windowMeshTexture, ivec3(tidx,5)).xyz;
    • Texture coordinate at p: a*t0 + b*t1 + c*t2
